Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1374–":"about 1374–Deceased","1374–Male":"1374–Deceased","1378–Female":"1378–Deceased","1400–Female":"1400–Deceased","1501–Male":"1501–Deceased","1348–Male":"1348–Deceased","1352–Female":"1352–Deceased","1348":"1348","1501":"1501","1400":"1400","1378":"1378","about 1501":"about 1501","1352":"1352","1374":"1374","about 1374":"about 1374","of Hendregyda,Abergele,Denbighshire,Wales":"Hendregyda, Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","of Plas Ystiwart,Abergele,Denbighshire,Wales":"Abergele, Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","of, Plas Ystiwart, Abergele, Denbighshire, Wales":"Abergele, Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tudur","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: from the Old Celtic form <i>Teutorix</i>, composed of elements meaning ‘people, tribe’ and ‘ruler, king’. It has been described as a Welsh form of <i>Theodore</i>, but there is no connection between them, though it is ultimately akin to the Germanic name <i>Theodoric</i> (  see  <b>Terry</b>   )."],"variants":[{"name":"Tudor","meanings":["Traditional: from the Old Celtic form <i>Teutorix</i>, composed of elements meaning ‘people, tribe’ and ‘ruler, king’. It has been described as a Welsh form of <i>Theodore</i>, but there is no connection between them, though it is ultimately akin to the Germanic name <i>Theodoric</i> (  see  <b>Terry</b>   )."]},{"name":"Tudyr","meanings":["Traditional: from the Old Celtic form <i>Teutorix</i>, composed of elements meaning ‘people, tribe’ and ‘ruler, king’. It has been described as a Welsh form of <i>Theodore</i>, but there is no connection between them, though it is ultimately akin to the Germanic name <i>Theodoric</i> (  see  <b>Terry</b>   )."]}]},{"name":"ab","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]},{"name":"Ieuan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin